<body><div class=WordSection1>
<div class="brand">📚 ENGLISH CODING · 영어코딩</div>
<h1>🖼️ WD001 Week 5 — English Worksheet</h1>
<p><strong>Topic:</strong> Images and Backgrounds — Visual Impact · <strong>Course:</strong> Web Design: CSS · <strong>Time:</strong> about 45 minutes</p>
<p>This week you make a big, bold <strong>hero section</strong> — a large background image with a heading sitting on top of it. You will use <code>background-image</code>, <code>background-size: cover</code> so the picture fills the space, and a dark overlay so white text stays readable on a busy photo.</p>
<hr />
<h2>1 · Predict 🔮</h2>
<p>Read each bit of CSS. Before you imagine the browser drawing it, write what you think will happen.</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;style&gt;
  .hero {
    background-image: url('beach.jpg');
    height: 400px;
  }
&lt;/style&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>A 400px-tall box with a background photo. Where does the photo appear?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;style&gt;
  .hero {
    background-image: url('beach.jpg');
    background-size: cover;
  }
&lt;/style&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>With <code>background-size: cover</code>, does the photo stretch to fill the whole box, or sit small in a corner?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;style&gt;
  .hero {
    color: white;
    background-color: black;
  }
&lt;/style&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>White text on a black background. Is the text easy or hard to read?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;style&gt;
  .hero h1 {
    font-size: 48px;
    color: white;
  }
&lt;/style&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>A 48px heading in white sitting on top of a photo. Do you think it looks small or like a big title?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>2 · Spot the Bug 🐛</h2>
<p>Each bit of CSS below was meant to do something, but it is broken. Read what it is <strong>supposed</strong> to do, then rewrite it so it works. After that, explain why the original was wrong and why your fix works.</p>
<p><strong>Bug A</strong> — The hero is supposed to show a background image, but nothing appears.</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;style&gt;
  .hero {
    background-image: beach.jpg;
    height: 400px;
  }
&lt;/style&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> a background image filename needs to be wrapped a certain way.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug B</strong> — The photo is supposed to fill the whole hero box, but it sits small and tiles/repeats instead.</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;style&gt;
  .hero {
    background-image: url('beach.jpg');
    height: 400px;
  }
&lt;/style&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> one line is missing that tells the image to fill the box.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug C</strong> — The heading is supposed to sit in the <strong>middle</strong> of the hero, but it is stuck in the top-left corner.</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;style&gt;
  .hero {
    background-image: url('beach.jpg');
    background-size: cover;
    height: 400px;
  }
&lt;/style&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> centring needs <code>display: flex</code> plus a way to centre across and down.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>3 · Build Your Hero Section 📸</h2>
<p>In Replit, add a <strong>hero section</strong> to the top of your page. Use a photo you like as the background and put a heading and a short line on top of it.</p>
<p>You can start from this and change the photo and the words:</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;div class=&quot;hero&quot;&gt;
  &lt;h1&gt;Hi, I'm ___&lt;/h1&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;A short line about me&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;style&gt;
  .hero {
    background-image: url('background.jpg');
    background-size: cover;
    background-position: center;
    height: 400px;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
    color: #ffffff;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .hero h1 {
    font-size: 48px;
  }
&lt;/style&gt;
</code></pre>
<p>If your text is hard to read on a busy photo, try giving the hero a darker background colour or a semi-transparent overlay so the white text pops.</p>
<p>When you finish, send a <strong>photo or video</strong> of your hero (or a picture of your code), then explain what you did. Use these sentence starters — write 4 to 6 sentences total.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The photo I chose for my hero is …</p>
<p><code>background-size: cover</code> made the image …</p>
<p>I centred my heading by …</p>
<p>To keep my text readable, I …</p>
<p>One tricky moment was when …</p>
<p>If I had more time, I would …</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>4 · Record Your Walkthrough 🎥</h2>
<p>Now take a video on your phone (or a parent's phone) while you show your hero section. Talk through it like you are teaching someone who has never made one. Try to use these words: <strong>hero</strong>, <strong>background</strong>, <strong>cover</strong>, <strong>centre</strong>, <strong>readable</strong>.</p>
<blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Show your hero section at the top of your page.</li>
<li>Read your <code>background-size: cover</code> line out loud and say what it does.</li>
<li>Show how your heading sits in the middle.</li>
<li>Show one thing you got wrong at first and how you fixed it.</li>
</ol>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Write what you will say in your video.</strong> Use the space below to plan it before you record — you can read from it while filming.</p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h3>Submit ✅</h3>
<p>Send this worksheet + your walkthrough video to teacher on KakaoTalk.</p>
